I’m proud to announce my latest remix treatment for the legendary songstress ROBERTA FLACK and her classic anthem “Killing Me Softly”! When I was approached by Warners to do this I honestly had some doubts it would be approved as Ms Flack has been known to turn down remixes forever! To my knowledge there’s only been one dance remix done by Steve Hurley over 30 years ago. To say this is a major accomplishment for me is an understatement! Big thanks to my brother @chrisrobonline on his masterful keyboard work. I realize that remixing a classic can be a risky task (if you care about the original song) but I always try my best to maintain integrity. The #remix is out now on all streaming platforms! Enjoy!

Many are aware of the remix I did for De La Soul’s “Stakes Is High” but only a select few die hards might know about this release. 

Back in 1999 I was fortunate enough to visit Dave’s home (thanks to my brother @truthenola ) to record this underground classic “Voicetress” which was originally released on a UK/P-VIne Japan compilation called Wide Angles. The drive from Brooklyn to Long Island had me in full geek mode. 

My Domecracker partner in beats @jocmax sent me the floppy disk with the loop, I chopped up the drums, programmed and arranged the beat in Dave’s basement on his SP-1200 and Akai 950, right in front of him. He was very attentive during the process. By the end of the session he told me I had shown him some tricks he never knew he could do. As you can imagine, this made my world. To be honest I was amazed that he even had this set up in his crib. At the time I knew that @plugwondelasoul and @inmaseowetrust made beats but I wonder till this day how many De La joints Dave actually produced. I’m sure that’s an impressive list and more than we can imagine. 

The whole experience was humbling. I was in the presence of Hip Hop royalty. #DeLaSoul played a major role in shaping my musical career path and Dave really made it ok to just be. There’s no other way TO be but you… without the facade. Frontin’ is for cornballs. Thank you Dave, the coolest of the cool. I’m still trying to come to grips. ❤️🙏🏾🕊 #arealone #trugoythedove #iloveyou #ripDave

Un evento imperdibile, unico e speciale in co-produzione con 𝗦𝗽𝗮𝘇𝗶𝗼 𝗠𝘂𝗿𝗮𝘁, che ha inserito l’appuntamento nel suo calendario di proposte di alto livello artistico e culturale.

Dj Spinna, Vincent E. Williams, è un fuoriclasse. Arriva da New York da cui esporta il sound di Brooklyn. Ha remixato artisti come De La Soul, Mary J. Blige e il suo amico Stevie Wonder. Leggendaria la festa Wonder-full a Brooklyn in cui Stevie Wonder sì esibì con DJ Spinna in numerose improvvisazioni.
Dopo essersi fatto conoscere nel mondo Hip-Hop, sempre alla ricerca di nuovi stimoli ha esplorato la musica house producendo anche numerosi brani oggi nella storia di questo tipo di produzione. Ha collaborato con produttori del calibro di Louie Vega e Kenny Dope, che insieme sono i Masters at Work.
Tra le altre collaborazioni di Dj Spinna citiamo anche quella con Eminem in “Three Six Five”, “Watch Deez” e “5-Star Generals”. E poi un remix proprio per Nicola Conte uscito lo scorso anno. 
Vincent E. Williams è stato uno dei protagonisti e promotori della dance e dell’hip hop, movimento artistico e culturale che nasce e si sviluppa per strada nel Bronx generando diverse correnti e stili afroamericani.
Tra le particolarità di Dj Spinna, i virtuosismi alla consolle, l’uso dei dischi in vinile e dei 45 giri.

#Enjoy ! #HipHop On The latest episode  of my *HERE TO THERE RADIO* show, this Friday 6.2.23 #Live @ 4PM (ET) on @applemusic I’m focusing on the record label ENJOY!  Enjoy records was a Harlem-based record label founded in 1962 by Bobby Robinson who had years of experience releasing R&B, Doo Wop and Blues records. By 1979 he would join the new Rap brigade of vinyl releases producing some of the hottest new talents emerging out of Harlem and the Bronx. Compared to Sugarhill record’s more polished productions, Enjoy boasted grittier and  funkier output with drummer Pumpkin and his All Stars band as the main backing band. Pumpkin provided the musical backdrop for the Treacherous Three, Spoonie G (Bobby’s Nephew), Grandmaster Flash and the Furious Five, and Funky Four plus 1, which included the first female MC Sha Rock @iammcsharock. I’ll go on record to say Rappin and Rocking the house by Funky Four + 1 personally changed me forever! Enjoy was the first label to release Doug E Fresh @therealdougefresh before “The Show” and Ladidadi with @therulernyc Slick Rick. So much history! #HipHopHistory

The late Ted Currier was a NYC Disco DJ pioneer who laid the foundation for the “radio mix show”, first on 92 “Disco” KTU then on WBLS under the helm of Frankie Crocker. By 1982, he quit radio to pursue the record industry, landing a position as A&R at Capitol/EMI Records. I had the honor of interviewing him for my P-Funk (Ep 95) of *HERE TO THERE RADIO* last year where he talked about signing @yolikegeorge and co-creating the groundbreaking “Atomic Dog”. We lost my friend Ted in late July of this year. This Friday 9.1. 23 starting at 4PM (ET) on the latest episode of my *HERE TO THERE RADIO* show on @applemusic I’m paying tribute to Ted as he was one of the first DJ pioneers I studied as a kid when DJing was still a new thing, especially on radio. 
Ted Currier was a masterful talent who crowned the mixing technique of overlaying (holding) two records together in the mix for long periods of time, the long blend. This was the pre-quantized disco era so you had to know your records! Ted also produced “Fly Girl” and “You Ain’t Fresh” by the Boogie Boys, which blew my mind once I realized the connection to his Disco past. He set a trend for producing various genres, a musical diversity I’ve always embraced. Tune into #HTTR  and explore this unsung hero’s catalog of artists he signed, produced and remixed. 💯#PureVIBEZ

Nas "Rewind" 
Special Inverse Groove Record!

Liscensed from Sony to create this high end packaging which includes a printed inner sleeve featuring the song's lyrics. There are two different pressings, a black version with a marketing sticker and a silver version with an obi strip.

This 45 is unlike any other record as the need is dropped in the middle of the record (where most records end) and plays outwards towards the outer edge of the record (where most records begin). This is very uncommon and is technically known as an "inverse groove" pressing which requires some wizardry from the cutting engineer who had to inverse the gears on his lathe during the cutting process in order to execute the cutting. Funny story: during the pressing process, the plant employees were so confused by this record during the QC testing they had to shut down operations to investigate why the record was not behaving like the standard pressings. 🤔
